author: @luke-bassett
text: Late to the party but I had an error that I didn't see mentioned before. I got an out of memory error for my VRAM on this line:  print('Accuracy:',accuracy.eval({x:mnist.test.images, y:mnist.test.labels}))  ResourceExhaustedError (see above for traceback): OOM when allocating tensor with shape[10000,32,28,28]  To get around it I set it up to calculate the accuracy in chunks. It works so I thought I'd post if here to help others, or so that anybody can point out any issues with this method that I may have overlooked.          hm_acc_chunks = 47 # how many chucnks to use when computing accuracy         sub_acc = []         for i in range(hm_acc_chunks):             start = int(len(mnist.test.images)*(hm_acc_chunks**-1)*i)              end = int(len(mnist.test.images)*(hm_acc_chunks**-1)*(i+1))             sub_acc.append(accuracy.eval({x:mnist.test.images[start:end], y:mnist.test.labels[start:end]}))          print('Accuracy:',sum(sub_acc)/len(sub_acc))

author: @sohaibarif2835
text: Alexnet is now quite old now but this was the network that made neural networks popular again in 2012. It is famous for winning the ImageNet 2012 competition. Now, one of the best ones is Inception v4 but I am not sure if the whole network is available. Fun fact, people still use the variable name fc7 when referring to fully connected layers to a conv layer due to the convention set in Alexnet where it was the 7th layer. This is despite networks today being 100s of layers (although, I did read some stuff about moving towards wide instead of deep networks meaning this could decrease) and fc7 clearly not being the 7th layer.
